TITLE: Applying Dynamic Styles to the Arrow Element in JavaScript
DESCRIPTION: Demonstrates how to use the arrow coordinates (`arrowX`, `arrowY`) obtained from `middlewareData` and the final `placement` to dynamically style the arrow element. It calculates the `staticSide` (the side the arrow attaches to) based on the placement and applies the `left`, `top`, and `staticSide` CSS properties to position the arrow correctly relative to the tooltip body.
SOURCE: https://github.com/floating-ui/floating-ui/blob/master/website/pages/docs/tutorial.mdx#2025-04-23_snippet_13

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
computePosition(button, tooltip, {
  placement: 'top',
  middleware: [
    offset(6),
    flip(),
    shift({padding: 5}),
    arrow({element: arrowElement}),
  ],
}).then(({x, y, placement, middlewareData}) => {
  Object.assign(tooltip.style, {
    left: `${x}px`,
    top: `${y}px`,
  });

  // Accessing the data
  const {x: arrowX, y: arrowY} = middlewareData.arrow;

  const staticSide = {
    top: 'bottom',
    right: 'left',
    bottom: 'top',
    left: 'right',
  }[placement.split('-')[0]];

  Object.assign(arrowElement.style, {
    left: arrowX != null ? `${arrowX}px` : '',
    top: arrowY != null ? `${arrowY}px` : '',
    right: '',
    bottom: '',
    [staticSide]: '-4px',
  });
});
```

